<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n08167b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n08" href="#n08167b">N08 (VI.B.6)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n08all.htm#n08167b"> 167(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Ward &mdash; grave of hills / Finglas &mdash; Slane</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><b>By the Way <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> The Ward</b> At the Drumcondra District Court the other day, writes a correspondent, the name of <mark>the Ward</mark> arose in connection with a licensing case, and as the locale is well known to users of the fine, straight road <mark>between Finglas and Slane</mark> it may be of interest to state the reason why the spot is so named. The name really belongs to the parish, which is situated in a comparatively elevated district. This place contains an ancient graveyard, and hence a significant derivation of its name is available from the Gaelic terms, which when joined, mean <mark>a grave of the hills</mark>. <small> <a name="FJ11feb24" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#FJ11feb24"><cite title="source">Freeman's Journal</cite></a> (11 February 1924) 8/6</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
